<div id="review_2332645101" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2332645101" />
    <a title="Biblio Curious" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26626256-biblio-curious"><img alt="Biblio Curious" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546381219p2/26626256.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2332645101?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Biblio Curious" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Biblio Curious" href="/user/show/26626256-biblio-curious">Biblio Curious</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781413511383" href="/book/show/2799614-ward-no-6">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26626256-biblio-curious?shelf=classics-western">classics-western</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2332645101" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4807181650089753297">Chekhov crams many ideas into a mere 34 pages. It&apos;s a very layered story that can be read from different points of view. I&apos;d love to do a comparison with this and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/254316.Cancer_Ward' title='Cancer Ward by Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn' rel='nofollow noopener'>Cancer Ward</a> someday. It can also be read with a historical context or in relation to Chekhov&apos;s other plays or his own life story I&apos;m sure. It&apos;s my 1st Checkhov work, so I read it out of context and as a single work.<br/><br/>The setting is a mental hospital that seems like a commentary on the ills of society. So I can&apos;t recommend it for folks wh</span>
  <span id="freeText4807181650089753297" style="display:none">Chekhov crams many ideas into a mere 34 pages. It's a very layered story that can be read from different points of view. I'd love to do a comparison with this and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/254316.Cancer_Ward" title="Cancer Ward by Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn" rel="nofollow noopener">Cancer Ward</a> someday. It can also be read with a historical context or in relation to Chekhov's other plays or his own life story I'm sure. It's my 1st Checkhov work, so I read it out of context and as a single work.<br /><br />The setting is a mental hospital that seems like a commentary on the ills of society. So I can't recommend it for folks who work in the health care field. Cancer Ward I can though. Why can't I recommend it for health care workers? It'll depress them with possibly offering no hope or solutions. It's a field that's tough enough without adding "healthy folks are descending into madness also."<br /><br />If we look at the Ward as a whole with all the parts that make it function, Stoicism would apply. Mental illness as the result of society is a possibility to examine. Later, we learn the city itself has a lot of illnesses in it. So the ward is a reflection of that. Within the ward, Nikita has the role to maintain order by any means necessary, to keep the status quo. The doctors provide drugs if you want to consider dystopian elements. <br /><br />At the end: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[My own interpretation once I neared the end of the text was more of a Faustian approach to it. The doctor "always read lying down." He took in knowledge as a hobby, something to simply enjoy &amp; once he became a doctor, life fell apart for him. Money became the deal with the devil &amp; 2 characters went on a fake vacation. That's where the devil really collected his fees and the doctor just gave in, he became less and less of a man with thoughts. Finally, on the last page the peasants rise up &amp; take charge once someone is dead. Death's the great equalizer. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />This great video gives an analysis of the meaning behind this great short story:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NAvY5xmHBpE">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NAvY5...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="4807181650089753297" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


